article.headline: Oregon State 72, California 64
article.story: BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Outside of a quick hug from his parents in the parking lot, Oregon State coach Jay John didn't make too much of the Beavers' first Pac-10 road win in nearly two years. That's because Oregon State' 72-64 win over conference-leading California on Saturday had many similarities to the Beavers' five previous road games this season, all of which ended in defeats. "(We) executed the game plan as well as we have ever on the road," John said. "It's just a matter of playing well and maturing in terms of our personality. We had been doing that all season. The good thing was tonight we got a result out of it." Nick DeWitz scored 18 points and Marcel Jones posted his second career double-double with 13 points and 11 rebounds to lead Oregon State to its first Pac-10 win on the road since the Beavers defeated Washington State, 65-58, on Feb. 12, 2004. Sasa Cuic added 16 points for the Beavers (8-6, 1-2), who had lost their first five games away from Gill Coliseum this season by an average of 13.8 points before defeating the first-place Bears on Saturday. California (9-4, 3-1) got 19 points and eight rebounds from Leon Powe but never did find an offensive rhythm against Oregon State's tight zone defense. The Bears trailed by as many as 14 against Oregon State and managed just two baskets during a critical seven-minute stretch late in the second half when the Beavers put the game away. "They came in with a sense of urgency and they did what they had to do," Powe said. "We didn't play that hard and kind of let down defensively a little bit. That's why we lost. Every time (the Beavers) got a good look they hit it." California coach Ben Braun lamented his team's effort against the Beavers, citing a lack of intensity as a prime factor in the loss which dropped the Bears into a three-way tie for first place in the Pac-10 with Arizona and UCLA. "I don't think we were very patient early," Braun said. "We were a pass or two short on every possession. We quick-shot it a couple of times with nobody underneath the basket. "Jay's team did a good job of taking tempo. They dribble-weaved about 25-30 seconds every possession. When we got stops and ran we were pretty successful but they shot (nearly) 60 percent so there wasn't a lot of stopping and running going on." California went into the game shooting 46.6 percent as a team and was riding high following the wins over USC and UCLA. Having defeated Oregon two days earlier, the Bears went into Saturday's game against Oregon State looking for its first 4-0 start in the Pac-10 since 2003. But California struggled against Oregon State's defense throughout the evening. The Bears opened the game missing 15 of their first 20 shot attempts then followed that with a 2-for-12 stretch to open the second half, allowing the Beavers to slowly pull away. California shot just 34.5 percent for the game while Oregon State made 56.3 percent of its shots. "We've been a good scoring team all season," John said. "Our problem has been turnovers. We didn't turn the ball over tonight, we made the extra passes and we hit the shots when we needed to hit them." After California pulled within 53-46 on Powe's steal and driving dunk with 8:42 to play, Oregon State put the game away with a 12-3 run over the next three minutes. Jones had six points in the run while DeWitz's six-foot jumper with 3:56 left gave the Beavers their biggest lead of the game at 63-49. The Bears made one final run at Oregon State, closing to 68-62 on Ayinde Ubaka's 3-pointer with 29 seconds remaining, but Chris Stephens sank four free throws in the next 17 seconds to secure the win for the Beavers. Stephens finished with 13 points. Ubaka and Richard Midgley had 12 points apiece for the Bears. Oregon State scored the first eight points of the game and sank its first three 3-point shots, building a 29-20 lead on Stephens' shot under the basket with 4:09 remaining. Powe, trying to become the first California player since 1992 to average a double-double for a season, got the Bears' going on their comeback with three straight points. Midgley then made three consecutive 3-pointers, pulling California within 34-32 going into halftime.
